\begin{abstract}
Dynamic and reliable switching among asynchronous clock sources is a persistent hurdle in advanced SoC and FPGA systems, where conventional clock multiplexers frequently suffer from glitches, metastability, or deadlock, especially when a clock source unexpectedly halts. This work introduces a glitch-free clock multiplexer architecture featuring autonomous and symmetric failover, permission-driven selection logic, and integrated activity sensing across clock domains. By combining cross-domain activity detection, a permission-based arbitration scheme, and a two-stage synchronizer with an augmented edge-capture mechanism, the design ensures clean, deterministic handover and robust system recovery without requiring an external reference clock. Asynchronous force-disable paths further guarantee safe transitions under all failure scenarios. Comprehensive simulation and FPGA prototyping on Intel Cyclone V validate the architecture’s effectiveness across normal operations, clock failures, and recovery events, with resource consumption as low as 12 ALMs and up to 496.52\,MHz operating frequency. Compared to timer-based and cross-coupled approaches, the proposed solution demonstrably enhances resiliency and determinism while maintaining compact hardware footprint.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Clock multiplexer, glitch-free switching, asynchronous clocks, failover, deadlock-free, FPGA, clock domain crossing
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section{Introduction}

As digital systems grow in complexity and demand greater adaptability, reliable clock switching becomes a critical concern, especially in applications such as system-on-chip (SoC) platforms and FPGA-based designs. Clock multiplexers, used to select between multiple clock sources for dynamic frequency scaling, power optimization, or fault recovery, must ensure robust and predictable operation to maintain system integrity.

However, ensuring seamless and safe transitions between asynchronous clock sources is non-trivial. Conventional multiplexing methods are often vulnerable to hazardous phenomena such as output glitches (unwanted pulses generated during select transitions) and metastability (unpredictable logic states arising from asynchronous control signal crossings). These effects can compromise downstream logic, induce timing violations, and ultimately threaten system reliability.

A range of prior architectures have attempted to address these issues through techniques such as break-before-make switching and watchdog-driven recovery. Yet, limitations remain: many solutions either compromise between glitch immunity and reliable failover, or introduce significant implementation overhead, manual intervention requirements, or susceptibility to deadlock and incomplete recovery.

Motivated by these challenges, this work presents a novel glitch-free clock multiplexer architecture capable of autonomous and safe switchover between asynchronous clock domains, even in the presence of faults or clock halts. Our design achieves robust functional safety and high speed with only modest resource overhead, as validated through FPGA implementation and detailed experimental comparisons.

The rest of this paper is organized as follows: Section~\ref{sec:related_work} reviews the limitations of conventional and state-of-the-art multiplexer designs. Section~\ref{sec:proposed_architecture} introduces the proposed architecture and its operation. Section~\ref{sec:results} presents functional verification and hardware evaluation, and Section~V concludes the work.




\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related_work}

\subsection{Challenges in Traditional Clock Multiplexer Design}

Conventional clock multiplexer designs, such as those based on combinational AND/OR logic, are prone to glitches and metastability. As shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:andor_mux_glitch_combined}, changes in the select \texttt{sel} input during active clock periods can lead to output glitches which are short, unwanted pulses violating set-up and hold times, and potentially propagating errors through sequential logic.

Additionally, asynchronous crossings without robust synchronization may induce metastability, especially when control signals like \texttt{sel} toggle near clock edges and are not protected by multi-stage synchronizers.

