\subsection{Motivation for This Work}

The prior architectures each tackle select failure modes: combinational designs offer simplicity, break-before-make (BBM) methods suppress glitches and metastability, and timer-based schemes add forced-safe outputs and automatic recovery. However, none alone guaranties glitch immunity, deadlock freedom, and fully autonomous, immediate switchover to any healthy clock source.

Our architecture intentionally integrates these advantages, while overcoming the remaining limitations, enabling robust failure detection, rapid and automatic switchover between clocks, and high-frequency operation within a unified framework.


\section{Proposed Architecture}
\label{sec:proposed_architecture}

This section presents the detailed architecture of the proposed glitch-free clock multiplexer. The system is composed of three functionally distinct but closely interconnected layers, as illustrated in Fig.~\ref{fig:block_diagram}. This layered approach enables rapid and robust failover in response to clock source failure, as well as reliable, glitch-free operation during clock transitions. While the architecture is designed to strongly favor switching to a functioning clock whenever possible, some rare or pathological failure scenarios may temporarily prevent immediate switchover; however, the system consistently seeks to activate any available live clock whenever feasible.

\subsection{System Overview}

Figure~\ref{fig:block_diagram} displays the high-level block diagram of the proposed clock multiplexer. The circuit accepts two asynchronous clock inputs \texttt{clk1}, \texttt{clk2} and a user selector \texttt{sel}, and outputs a single glitch-free clock \texttt{clk\_out}. Internally, the design is decomposed into three sequential processing layers, each with clearly delineated responsibilities:

\begin{itemize}
    \item{Layer 1: Activity Sensor} : Continuously monitors the activity of each input clock by sampling it using the other clock's domain. For each clock, a real-time health signal is generated that indicates whether that specific clock is considered failed, as observed by the opposite clock domain.
    \item \textbf{Layer 2: Decision Making} : Receives the individual clock health signals from Layer 1 along with the user preference, and uses this information to dynamically select which clock should be considered for output. This layer generates “desired clock” signals, which indicate the preferred source based on current operating conditions but do not directly control the output gating logic.
    \item \textbf{Layer 3: Safe Handover} : Converts the “desired clock” signals from Layer 2 into the final output enables, guaranteeing that only one clock is active at the output at any time. It implements synchronized enable registers and mutual exclusion logic to ensure all switching is glitch-free, honoring the break-before-make principle during clock transitions.
\end{itemize}

This modular decomposition, as visually depicted in Fig.~\ref{fig:block_diagram}, clarifies both the dataflow and the control dependencies of the system, and forms the basis for ease of analysis and future extensibility.

