\subsection{Layer 1: Activity Sensor}
The bottom layer, Activity Sensor, interfaces directly with the two asynchronous clock domains. Utilizing cross-domain sampling, each clock is sampled in the other’s domain, and transitions are detected by XORing consecutive samples\cite{9217816}. A saturating synchronous counter, running in the opposing clock domain, accumulates the number of cycles since the last detected transition. If this counter exceeds a predefined threshold (set here to 3), a failure flag (\texttt{fail1} or \texttt{fail2}) is asserted for that clock. This approach robustly distinguishes between brief jitter and true clock failure, and ensures fast detection without the need for a reference clock. The outputs of this layer, \texttt{fail1} and \texttt{fail2}, abstractly represent the health status of \texttt{clk1} and \texttt{clk2}, and are passed forward in the block diagram as shown.

\subsection{Layer 2: Decision Making}

Layer 2 is responsible for real-time assessment and selection of the appropriate clock source for system output. Its operation relies on two key pieces of information: the health status of each input clock (as indicated by Layer~1) and the user’s clock selection preference.

