    \caption{Schematic of layered clock failover system, showing Activity Sensor, Decision Making, and Safe Handover logic for each clock domain. Mutual exclusion, synchronization, and safe output enforcement are all handled in Layer 3.}
    \label{fig:schematic_diagram}
\end{figure*}

The decision-making policy is as follows:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{User Preference:} The system gives priority to the clock preferred by the user, as long as it is functioning correctly.
    \item \textbf{Automatic Switchover:} If the preferred clock fails but the alternative is still active, the system immediately designates the healthy clock as the desired source to maintain output continuity.
    \item \textbf{Safe Output State:} If both input clocks are inactive, Layer~2 will, in most cases, prevent either clock from being selected, allowing the output to transition to a defined safe state as governed by Layer~3. However, in rare situations—such as during critical timing events, protocol restrictions, or asynchronous transitions—the system may not be able to enforce the safe state immediately, but will do so as soon as operational conditions permit.
\end{itemize}




Throughout normal operation and during faults, Layer 2 continually determines the appropriate source to use, producing “desired clock” signals that encode the system’s clock selection intent at every instant. These signals serve as guidance for Layer 3, which implements glitch-free handover and output gating.

This policy enables rapid and robust responses to clock source failures, minimizing disruption and supporting scenarios ranging from straightforward preference enforcement to complex recovery situations. Verification of these outcomes, including handling of the safe output state, is presented in the subsequent results section.

\subsection{Layer 3: Safe Handover}

Layer 3 is responsible for safely implementing the clock selection determined by the Decision Making layer. Its core objective is to guarantee glitch-free and mutually exclusive switching between the two clock sources which ensure that only one source is ever enabled at a time, and that transitions do not cause spurious output or timing hazards.


