\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Enable Synchronization, Pipelining, and Output Gating:}
    As illustrated in the block diagram  Fig.~\ref{fig:block_diagram}, the “desired clock” signals from the Decision Making block are passed through dedicated flip-flop stages within each respective clock domain. These synchronizers play several roles: they \emph{safely align enables to each clock domain}, \emph{facilitate pipelining for improved timing and reduced critical path}, and \emph{ensure enables change only on valid, stable clock edges}. This architectural principle avoids hazards and glitches, commonly seen with direct combinational gating.

    \item \textbf{Mutual Exclusion and Break-Before-Make:}
    The mutual exclusion logic, also outlined at a high level in Fig.~\ref{fig:block_diagram}, ensures that both output enables cannot ever be active simultaneously. This guaranties what is called break-before-make switching, which ensures clean, monotonic transitions at the output without the risk of simultaneous or glitchy clock drives. The detailed circuit implementation of this logic is further depicted in the schematic diagram in Fig.~\ref{fig:schematic_diagram}.

    \item \textbf{Safe Output State:}
    The principle of holding \texttt{clk\_out} in a safe, inactive state (typically logic low) whenever no valid clock is available, such as when both inputs are inactive, reset is asserted, or synchronization dictates a temporary pause, which is incorporated at the top level in the block diagram (Fig.~\ref{fig:block_diagram}) and realized concretely in the output gating elements shown in the detailed schematic (Fig.~\ref{fig:schematic_diagram}).
\end{itemize}



