\section{Results and Evaluation}
\label{sec:results}
\subsection{Simulation and Functional Verification}

To validate the correctness and reliability of the proposed design, the system was simulated under a range of critical scenarios. These test cases thoroughly exercise both normal operation and various fault conditions, including clock failure, recovery, and dual-stop situations.

\textbf{Test case 1: Selected clock fails, alternate clock remains active (with full recovery even after both clocks fail)} \\
When the selected clock (\texttt{clk2}) ceases toggling while the selector (\texttt{sel}) remains unchanged, but the other clock (\texttt{clk1}) remains active, the output (\texttt{clk\_out}) seamlessly switches to and tracks the remaining live clock. \textbf{Remarkably, even if both clocks become inactive and \texttt{clk\_out} is forced to a safe state (logic Low), the system will immediately and automatically resume correct operation—tracking any clock source that becomes active again, without requiring any selector update.} This robust functional recovery is demonstrated by the waveform in Fig.~\ref{fig:simu_main1}; specifically, the \textbf{leftmost circled region} highlights the output’s recovery immediately after both clocks become inactive and then one resumes operation.

\textbf{Test case 2: Selected clock recovers after failure} \\
Demonstrating system flexibility, if the previously selected clock (\texttt{clk1}) resumes toggling after being stuck, the output (\texttt{clk\_out}) returns to following this clock as soon as it recovers, as seen in the latter portion of Fig.~\ref{fig:simu_main1}.

