\subsection{FPGA Implementation and Resource Utilization}
All architectures were designed in Verilog HDL and synthesized for the Intel Cyclone V 5CEFA2F23C8 FPGA. The measured resource utilization and timing performance for each design are summarized in Table~\ref{tab:bbm_timer_prop_compare}, enabling a direct side-by-side comparison under consistent tool and device conditions.

Table~\ref{tab:bbm_timer_prop_compare} reveals that the break-before-make (BBM) design achieves the lowest area consumption, requiring only 3 ALMs, 2 LABs, 4 ALUTs, and 6 DLRs, and reaches the highest maximum frequency at 580.05\,MHz. However, this minimalism comes at the price of compromised functionality, as the BBM design lacks both deadlock-free operation and dual-stop safety. The timer-based architecture improves functional reliability with deadlock-free switching, but still fails to provide dual-stop safety. This approach sees a moderate increase in resource usage (12 ALMs, 4 LABs, 5 ALUTs, 10 DLRs) and attains a reduced maximum frequency of 367.92\,MHz due to frequency-dependent timing overhead.

By contrast, the proposed GFCM architecture delivers an unique combination of full glitch-free behavior, deadlock avoidance, and dual-stop safety---all with constant-latency operation. While GFCM exhibits a moderate area increase (14 ALMs, 3 LABs, 24 ALUTs, 22 DLRs) relative to BBM, it achieves a high maximum operating frequency of 515.46\,MHz---substantially higher than the timer-based scheme and only slightly below the resource-minimal BBM design. This demonstrates an advantageous trade-off: a modest increase in hardware resources enables not only high-speed operation, but also robust, autonomous fault recovery and safe performance even under extreme failure scenarios, which cannot be guaranteed by the other two designs. Thus, the proposed GFCM is exceptionally suited for demanding applications that prioritize both performance and functional safety.






\section{Conclusion}

This work has presented a robust, glitch-free clock multiplexer architecture capable of fully autonomous and safe switchover between asynchronous clock sources. By integrating the key strengths of traditional combinational, break-before-make, and timer-based schemes, the proposed GFCM solution achieves comprehensive coverage of failure scenarios, ensuring glitch immunity, deadlock freedom, and immediate recovery without manual intervention.

Functional verification confirmed the system’s ability to sustain seamless operation and failover across a broad range of test conditions, while FPGA implementation results on the Intel Cyclone V 5CEFA2F23C8 device demonstrated that these advanced safety features are achieved with modest resource overhead and competitive maximum frequency. Comparative analysis highlighted superior performance and resilience over established approaches, making the proposed architecture well-suited for safety-critical and high-availability digital systems.

Future work may extend this framework to support multiplexers with more than two clock domains, or further optimize the architecture for ultra-low-power or high-performance applications. Additional directions include adaptive thresholding for failure detection by exploiting input clock frequency ratios, as well as enhancing monitoring efficiency through resource-optimized or pseudo-randomized counter designs.
